<br /></p>

<hr />

<p>Perhaps this is what happened between Blanchot and Foucault: not seeing each other, keeping a pure distance, without any pollution of the world, leaving the friend in a state of absolute freedom. At the same time, pay attention to each other, comment on each other, and communicate with each other in the way of writing and reading. There is no â€œpersonal friendshipâ€ in this kind of friendship. This is what Blanchot calls an â€œintellectual friendship.â€ However, this kind of friendship is never spoken out easily. This kind of friendship needs to be maintained in a silent way. The words and declarations of this kind of friendship are not an affirmation of it, but a depletion of it. A friend can be claimed only when the friend is gone forever, only when the friend never hears the name friend. It was also when Foucault could never listen that Blanchot began to declare this friendship openly: yes, Foucault was his friend. â€œFriendship is a gift that is promised to Foucault behind you. It goes beyond strong emotions, beyond contemplation, beyond life-threateningâ€¦ I firmly believe that no matter how embarrassing the situation may be, I remain faithful to this An intellectual friendship. Foucaultâ€™s death grieves me, but it allows me to declare this friendship to him today.â€
<br />
<br />
æˆ–è®¸ï¼Œåœ¨å¸ƒæœ—è‚–å’Œç¦æŸ¯ä¹‹é—´å‘ç”Ÿçš„å°±æ˜¯è¿™ç±»å‹è°Šï¼šä¸è§é¢ï¼Œä¿æŒçº¯å‡€çš„è·ç¦»ï¼Œæ²¡æœ‰ä¸–ä¿—çš„ä»»ä½•æ±¡æŸ“ï¼Œä»è€Œè®©æœ‹å‹å¤„åœ¨ç»å¯¹çš„è‡ªç”±çŠ¶æ€ã€‚ä¸æ­¤åŒæ—¶ï¼Œä»¥å†™ä½œå’Œé˜…è¯»çš„æ–¹å¼ï¼Œå…³æ³¨å¯¹æ–¹ï¼Œè¯„è®ºå¯¹æ–¹ï¼Œå’Œå¯¹æ–¹å½¼æ­¤äº¤æµã€‚è¿™ç§å‹è°Šä¸å­˜åœ¨â€œç§äº¤â€ã€‚è¿™å°±æ˜¯å¸ƒæœ—è‚–æ‰€è¯´çš„â€œçŸ¥è¯†å‹è°Šâ€ã€‚ä½†æ˜¯ï¼Œè¿™ç§å‹è°Šä»ä¸è½»æ˜“åœ°è¯´å‡ºæ¥ï¼Œè¿™ç§å‹è°Šéœ€è¦ä»¥æ²‰é»˜çš„æ–¹å¼æ¥ç»´æŠ¤ï¼Œå¯¹è¿™ç§å‹è°Šçš„è¨€è¯´å’Œå®£ç§°ï¼Œä¸æ˜¯å¯¹å®ƒçš„è‚¯å®šï¼Œè€Œæ˜¯å¯¹å®ƒçš„æŸè€—ã€‚æœ‹å‹ï¼Œåªæœ‰åœ¨æœ‹å‹æ°¸è¿œåœ°ç¦»å¼€çš„æ—¶å€™ï¼Œåªæœ‰æœ‹å‹æ°¸è¿œå¬ä¸åˆ°æœ‹å‹è¿™ä¸ªç§°å‘¼çš„æ—¶å€™ï¼Œæ‰å¯ä»¥è¢«å®£ç§°ã€‚ä¹Ÿæ­£æ˜¯åœ¨ç¦æŸ¯æ°¸è¿œæ— æ³•å€¾å¬çš„æ—¶å€™ï¼Œå¸ƒæœ—è‚–æ‰å¼€å§‹å…¬å¼€åœ°å®£ç¤ºè¿™ç§å‹è°Šï¼šæ˜¯çš„ï¼Œç¦æŸ¯æ˜¯ä»–çš„æœ‹å‹ã€‚â€œå‹è°Šæ˜¯è®¸è¯ºåœ¨èº«åèµ ç»™ç¦æŸ¯çš„ç¤¼ç‰©ã€‚å®ƒè¶…è¶Šäºå¼ºçƒˆæƒ…æ„Ÿä¹‹å¤–ï¼Œè¶…è¶Šäºæ€ç´¢é—®é¢˜ä¹‹å¤–ï¼Œè¶…è¶Šäºç”Ÿå‘½å±é™©ä¹‹å¤–â€¦â€¦æˆ‘åšä¿¡ï¼Œä¸ç®¡å¤„å¢ƒå¤šä¹ˆå°´å°¬ï¼Œæˆ‘ä»ç„¶å¿ å®äºè¿™ä¸€ä»½çŸ¥è¯†å‹è°Šã€‚ç¦æŸ¯çš„é€ä¸–ä»¤æˆ‘æ‚²ç—›ä¸å·²ï¼Œä½†å®ƒå´å…è®¸æˆ‘ä»Šå¤©å‘ä»–å®£ç¤ºè¿™ä»½å‹è°Šã€‚â€</p>
<hr />

<p><br />
<br /></p>

<hr />

<p>Although Foucault can no longer declare this friendship to Blanchotâ€”two friends, one has to go first, one cannot declare friendship openly to the otherâ€”but we can still imagine Foucault agreeing Blanchotâ€™s approach. For, after the death of Roland Barthes, what Foucault expressed about friendship in his memorial speech bears a striking resemblance to what Blanchot said. It was also after Barthesâ€™s death that Foucault declared this friendship. Foucault said that Roland Barthes â€œhas gained social recognition for more than two decades of unremitting efforts, and has produced important research results of originality, which have spared me from my friendship with himâ€¦ Allow me to disclose this this afternoon.â€ The only friendship. This friendship is at least reticently similar to the death it hates.â€ Likewise, friendship can only be revealed after death; friendship happens only in silence; friendship is not any pragmatic tool. Isnâ€™t that what Blanchot said to the late Foucault?
<br />
<br />
