<hr />

<p><br />
<br /></p>

<hr />

<p>Blanchot ends his commemorative essay with a quote from Aristotle: â€œFriend, there is no friend in the world.â€ Often, this is a curious oxymoron: how can one be called a friend? , how can you face a friend, but at the same time tell him that there are no friends in the world? But, in Blanchot, there is absolutely no paradox in this sentence: yes, Foucault is no longer a friend. So, now, I can call him my friend. This is a â€œno personalâ€ friend, a silent friend, a pure â€œintellectual friendshipâ€.
